		h2#terms.mt-5 Term Dates
		hr
		p There are three terms every academic year in Oxford, with weird names.
		ul 
			li Michaelmas Term - early October to early December
			li Hilary Term - mid January to mid March
			li Trinity Term - late April to late June

		p Each term is 8 weeks long, which is an extremely short time to squeeze everything in. As a side effect, we will have collections (a mini exam) after each break, so around half of the six-week long holiday between terms is usually used as revision (at least for me). The term breaks are really the time I managed to digest all the content last term and get ready for another hectic eight weeks. 


		h2#course.mt-5 My Course
		p My course is 4-year course with an integrated master's degree. (I could choose to leave after third year with a bachelor's degree, but that's a decision for future me)
		p The Computer Science courses in Oxford feels a lot more math oriented than I thought. I was quite shocked by the amount of Mathematics I saw at first. But now I understand that good foundation in Math (especially Linear Algebra) is crucial to truly understand Artificial Intelligence and Computer Graphics. Besides, the practical things like making websites and such can be self-taught, which is what I have been doing over the years. 
		p A typical week for a first year: We will have around 8 hours of lectures per week. We have around 3 tutorials per week, which are small group teaching sessions (usually 1 to 2-3), it is a good learning opportunity to clarify something that I am not too sure, to ask questions, and to learn more about the topic in general. Although each of them is only 1 hour long, what usually takes more time are the problem sheets (worksheets) that we have to complete before each tutorial.  
		p Things might be more hectic next year, I will see...
		p There are no common cores (i.e. courses that are not too related to your subject), which is extremely great for somebody who enjoys Computer Science like me.

		h2#bike.mt-5 Biking in Oxford
		p As I said my college is only moderately sized, meaning that I will have to live offsite in my second and fourth year. Knowing that I might need a bike next year, I bought one in March. Riding a bike on the road is certainly scary, but quite fun as well. :) (More updates on that later)

